{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622730"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:05:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:05:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16809"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16809"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.03,0,0.89]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9500"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67244"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9500"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52696"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5225"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22503"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67244"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe acute abdominal pain. The medical team decides to administer intravenous morphine for pain management.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the drug\u0027s primary mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["N-methyl-D-aspartate receptor antagonist","Delta opioid receptor antagonist","Gamma-aminobutyric acid receptor agonist","Kappa opioid receptor partial agonist","Mu opioid receptor agonist"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMorphine primarily acts as a \u003Cstrong\u003Emu opioid receptor agonist\u003C/strong\u003E in the central nervous system. This action produces its characteristic effects of analgesia, sedation, and euphoria, along with side effects such as respiratory depression and constipation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EN-methyl-D-aspartate receptor antagonist\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of ketamine, which is used as an anaesthetic and analgesic agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelta opioid receptor antagonist\u003C/strong\u003E: while morphine has some activity at delta receptors, it acts as an agonist rather than an antagonist, and this is not its primary mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGamma-aminobutyric acid receptor agonist\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of benzodiazepines and barbiturates, which are used primarily as anxiolytics and sedatives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKappa opioid receptor partial agonist\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect; morphine acts as a full rather than partial agonist at its target receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe interaction of morphine with mu opioid receptors leads to decreased neurotransmitter release and reduced pain signal transmission in the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Morphine acts primarily as an agonist at mu opioid receptors in the central nervous system.","The main therapeutic effects of morphine include analgesia, sedation, and euphoria.","Key side effects of morphine include respiratory depression, constipation, and nausea."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52696"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16809"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52696"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T10:36:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T10:37:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9500"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67244"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"t